Myofibroblast transdifferentiation: The dark force in ocular wound healing and fibrosis.
Progress in retinal and eye research (2017)
This review discusses epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) and the loss of epithelial markers including E-cadherin and tight junction proteins during transdifferentiation. The downregulation of cell motility (NES -5.08) and maintenance of high E-cadherin expression in this cluster suggests these epithelial cells are not undergoing EMT, supporting the stable epithelial cell annotation.

Disease Association

This epithelial cell cluster is not associated with any classical disease state but represents a physiologically active, secretory epithelial population central to axolotl limb regeneration. The cells exhibit a canonical epithelial signature with high expression of EPCAM, E-cadherin, desmosomal components (DSP, DSC2, PKP1-3), and secretory markers (AGR2 homologs, mucin-3A-like), confirming their identity as wound epidermis or apical epithelial cap (AEC) cells. These cells are not malignant or pathological but are instead essential regenerative effectors that form the signaling niche for blastema formation. Their upregulation of proteasomal degradation and vesicle-mediated transport reflects intense protein turnover required for secretion of growth factors (e.g., FGFs, BMPs) and mucins that maintain the regenerative microenvironment. The enrichment in immune-related pathways (cytokine signaling, innate immunity) underscores their role as immune-active barriers, coordinating inflammation resolution and tissue remodeling. The downregulation of cell motility and ECM organization aligns with their anchored, polarized stateunlike fibroblasts or mesenchymal cells, they do not migrate into the blastema but instead serve as a stable signaling platform. The presence of these cells across non-regenerating, intact, and regenerating samples confirms their baseline role in skin homeostasis and their dynamic upregulation during regeneration. No disease ontology term applies; this is a functional, non-pathological epithelial state critical for regeneration, analogous to mammalian wound healing but uniquely amplified and sustained in axolotls.

Therapeutic Approach

The identified epithelial cell cluster corresponds to the wound epidermis and apical epithelial cap (AEC) in axolotl limb regenerationspecialized secretory epithelial cells critical for blastema formation and regenerative signaling. While no FDA-approved drugs directly target axolotl epithelial cells, human therapeutics targeting analogous wound-healing epithelial functions offer mechanistic insights. Topical agents such as sodium hyaluronate (e.g., Hylase Wound, IPM Wound) and benzalkonium chloride-based cleansers promote epithelial migration, hydration, and barrier restoration in human wounds, mirroring the AECs role in maintaining a proliferative microenvironment. Allantoin-containing formulations enhance re-epithelialization by modulating keratinocyte proliferation and reducing inflammation. The high expression of AGR2 homologs and mucins suggests a secretory burden akin to goblet or glandular epithelia; thus, agents supporting ER protein folding (e.g., chemical chaperones like 4-PBA) could theoretically enhance mucin processing efficiency in regenerating tissue. The upregulated proteasome and vesicular transport pathways indicate active protein turnover; proteasome inhibitors like bortezomib are contraindicated here as they would disrupt essential secretion, whereas enhancers of ER-Golgi trafficking (e.g., small molecules targeting COPII components) represent novel investigational targets. Notably, the absence of immune cell markers confirms this is not an inflammatory or neoplastic state, so immunosuppressants are irrelevant. Instead, growth factor delivery systems (FGF2, BMP7) that mimic AEC signaling may accelerate regeneration. Future opportunities include biomaterial scaffolds functionalized with AEC-derived exosomes or engineered to express key ligands (e.g., FGF8), creating synthetic signaling niches. This cluster underscores that regeneration is not merely cellular proliferation but requires precise epithelial signalinga paradigm shift from traditional drug discovery toward bioengineered microenvironment modulation.

Justification

Evidence Analysis

Initial Hypothesis Selection

Hypothesis 1 (Tissue-resident macrophages) emerges as the most supported hypothesis based on comprehensive marker expression analysis and functional pathway enrichment. While all five hypotheses propose myeloid cell identities, the evidence strongly distinguishes tissue-resident macrophages from other alternatives.

Core Supporting Evidence

Canonical Macrophage Markers:
The cluster exhibits exceptionally strong expression of core macrophage identity markers:

  • AIF1 (92.46%) - canonical macrophage/microglia marker
  • CSF1R (87.79%) - macrophage colony-stimulating factor receptor, essential for macrophage development and survival
  • C1QB (88.96%) and C1QC (83.47%) - complement components highly characteristic of tissue-resident macrophages
  • CYBA (93.63%) - component of NADPH oxidase complex for phagocytic oxidative burst
  • CD68 (80.68%) - lysosomal marker strongly associated with macrophage phagocytic activity
  • MARCO (67.73%) - scavenger receptor for pathogen recognition and phagocytosis

Phagocytic and Lysosomal Machinery:
Robust expression of genes supporting phagocytosis and antigen processing:

  • LYZ (99.68%) - lysozyme for bacterial degradation
  • CTSD (80.68%), CTSB (81.35%), CTSS (69.04%) - cathepsins for protein degradation
  • LAMP1 (67.16%), LAMP2 (29.58%) - lysosomal-associated membrane proteins
  • HEXB (46.78%) - lysosomal enzyme
  • PLBD1 (86.87%) - phospholipase involved in lipid remodeling

Antigen Presentation and Immune Regulation:

  • CD74 (96.82%) - MHC class II-associated invariant chain for antigen presentation
  • LGALS9 (90.34%) - galectin-9 for immune regulation and T cell modulation
  • ITM2C (89.81%) - immune cell function
  • FCER1G (71.62%) - Fc receptor gamma chain for immune complex recognition
  • TLR2 (46.28%) - toll-like receptor for pathogen recognition

Transcription Factors and Lineage Markers:

  • SPI1 (80.86%) - PU.1 transcription factor essential for myeloid lineage
  • IRF8 (10.33%) - interferon regulatory factor for myeloid differentiation

Pathway Enrichment Alignment

The functional enrichment strongly supports macrophage identity:

  • Innate immune system (NES=6.50 differential, 8.83 singleSample) - primary macrophage function
  • Neutrophil degranulation (NES=4.85) - shared myeloid granule content
  • Toll-like receptor cascades (NES=4.10) - pattern recognition
  • Lipid metabolism (NES=4.07 differential, 5.02 singleSample) - membrane remodeling and lipid antigen presentation
  • Downregulated ECM pathways - consistent with immune rather than stromal function

Rejection of Alternative Hypotheses

Hypothesis 2 (Microglia-like cells) - REJECTED:
Critical microglia-specific markers are absent:

  • TMEM119 (0.18%), P2RY12 (0.0%), SALL1 (1.24%), CX3CR1 (0.0%), OLFML3 (1.38%)
    These markers distinguish CNS-resident microglia from peripheral macrophages and are essentially absent, definitively ruling out microglia identity despite shared expression of AIF1 and CSF1R.

Hypothesis 3 (Monocyte-derived macrophages) - REJECTED:
Complete absence of monocyte recruitment and differentiation markers:

  • CCR2 (0.0%) - monocyte chemokine receptor
  • LY6C (0.0%) - monocyte marker
  • S100A4 (0.0%), VCAN (0.0%), FCN1 (0.0%) - inflammatory monocyte markers
    The absence of these markers indicates these are established tissue-resident macrophages rather than recently recruited monocyte-derived cells, despite the wound healing context (3dpa timepoint).

Hypothesis 4 (Dendritic cells) - REJECTED:
Dendritic cell-specific markers are completely absent:

  • ITGAX/CD11c (0.0%), FLT3 (0.99%), CD209 (0.0%), CLEC9A (0.0%), XCR1 (0.0%)
  • HLA-DRA (0.0%), HLA-DRB1 (0.0%) - MHC class II molecules
  • CD86 (0.0%), CD80 (0.0%) - co-stimulatory molecules
    The high expression of macrophage markers CD68 and MARCO contradicts dendritic cell identity. While CD74 expression suggests antigen presentation capacity, this is consistent with macrophage function.

Hypothesis 5 (MDSCs) - REJECTED:
Key MDSC markers are absent:

  • S100A8 (0.0%), S100A9 (0.0%) - granulocytic MDSC markers
  • NOS2 (0.99%), IDO1 (0.0%) - immunosuppressive enzymes
  • ARG1 (7.61%) - minimal expression
    The expression pattern reflects mature macrophages rather than immunosuppressive myeloid cells.

Macrophage Polarization State

Not Classically Polarized M2 Macrophages:
Despite the regenerative context, classic M2 markers are absent:

  • CD163 (0.0%), MRC1 (0.0%), TREM2 (0.0%)

Not Pro-inflammatory M1 Macrophages:
Pro-inflammatory markers are appropriately low:

  • NOS2 (0.99%), IL1B (0.0%), TNF (0.0%)

Interpretation: These are tissue-resident macrophages in an activated surveillance state during wound healing, expressing complement components (C1QB, C1QC) and phagocytic machinery without strong M1/M2 polarization. The high expression of APOE (93.56%), CD5L (38.11%), and GPNMB (31.17%) suggests involvement in lipid metabolism and tissue homeostasis characteristic of tissue-resident populations.

Biological Context Integration

The cluster composition (100% immune cells, 75% from 3dpa timepoint, distributed across wound_healing samples) aligns with tissue-resident macrophages responding to limb injury. These cells are:

  1. Established residents (not recently recruited, based on absence of monocyte markers)
  2. Activated for immune surveillance (high innate immune pathway enrichment)
  3. Engaged in phagocytosis and debris clearance (lysosomal machinery, complement)
  4. Providing immune regulation (LGALS9, CD74 for antigen presentation)

Granular Annotation Justification

The granular annotation "AIF1+/CSF1R+/C1Q+ phagocytic tissue-resident macrophage with complement-mediated immune surveillance function" captures:

  • Core identity markers (AIF1, CSF1R)
  • Distinctive complement expression (C1Q components)
  • Primary function (phagocytic, immune surveillance)
  • Tissue-resident rather than recruited status

Limitations and Uncertainties

  1. Axolotl-specific considerations: Some mammalian macrophage markers may not be conserved or detectable in axolotl
  2. M2 marker absence: Unexpected given regenerative context, but may reflect species differences or specific regeneration phase
  3. LYZ expression: Listed as negative marker in Hypothesis 1 but highly expressed (99.68%); however, LYZ is broadly expressed in myeloid cells and supports phagocyte identity rather than contradicting it

Conclusion

Tissue-resident macrophages is the definitive annotation, supported by canonical macrophage markers, phagocytic machinery, complement expression, and functional pathway enrichment, while all alternative hypotheses are rejected due to absence of their specific defining markers.

Review Comments

Expert Assessment Integration

The five expert assessments converge on a unified conclusion: this cluster represents a tissue-resident macrophage with a unique, axolotl-specific functional program. While all experts validate the core identity through near-universal expression of AIF1, CSF1R, C1QB, C1QC, CYBA, and CD68, they diverge critically on evolutionary interpretation. The immunologist and integrator highlight the absence of mammalian lipid-handling partners (LIPA, FABP4, MS4A7) despite high APOE, suggesting decoupled metabolic regulation. The developmental biologist notes the complete absence of yolk sac transcription factors (RUNX1, PU.1_SV), challenging the assumption of embryonic origin. The functional immunologist emphasizes the LGALS9-driven immune modulation as a non-canonical alternative to M2 polarization. Crucially, all agree that low IRF8 (10.33%) reflects regulatory divergence, not contamination or immaturity.

Biological Context

This population operates within the dynamic regenerative niche of dpa3 limb tissue, where ECM suppression (COL1A1, ELN downregulated) and active debris clearance are paramount. Unlike mammalian macrophages that polarize into M1/M2 states during repair, these cells exhibit a non-polarized surveillance phenotypelacking both pro-inflammatory (NOS2, TNF) and reparative (CD163, TREM2) markers. Their high LYZ (99.68%) and complement components suggest an evolutionarily enhanced antimicrobial defense strategy suited to the axolotls non-sterile wound environment. The co-expression of APOE with PLBD1 and NPC2 indicates lipid scavenging from damaged myofibers is central to their function, likely fueling membrane biogenesis for motility and phagosome formation during blastema expansion.

Confidence & Heterogeneity Considerations

The High confidence level is fully justified: the concordance of 7+ core markers across >80% of cells forms an unambiguous signature. The heterogeneity status of False is equally robustno expert detected evidence of mixed populations. Discrepancies in IRF8, RUNX1, or CST3 expression reflect lineage-specific adaptation, not cellular diversity. This cluster exhibits molecular homogeneity at the transcriptomic level; the observed variations are evolutionary noise within a single lineagenot subtypes. The absence of monocyte (CCR2), dendritic cell (FLT3), or fibroblast (PDGFRB) markers definitively rules out contamination.

Alternative Interpretations

Two compelling alternatives emerge: First, these may represent an evolutionarily ancient myeloid state predating the divergence of M2 polarization pathways in mammalsa "pre-M2" sentinel optimized for debris clearance without inflammatory amplification. Second, they could be adult hematopoietic-derived macrophages that have lost embryonic TFs upon maturation but retained residency via CSF1R signalingan ontogeny distinct from yolk sac-derived counterparts. The latter is supported by high SPI1 without RUNX1/PU.1_SV expression.

Biological Significance

This population embodies a key innovation in axolotl regeneration: immune surveillance uncoupled from inflammation or fibrosis. By deploying complement opsonization and lysozyme-mediated killing while suppressing collagen synthesis via unknown paracrine signals (potentially TGFB1-driven), these macrophages create a permissive microenvironment for dedifferentiation and blastema growth. Their reliance on APOE without LIPA/FABP4 suggests lipids are conserved for structural roles rather than catabolisma metabolic economy critical under regenerative stress. The dominance of LGALS9 over IL-10 implies T-cell modulation occurs through galectin-9s interaction with TIM-3 on lymphocytes rather than classical anti-inflammatory cytokines. This represents not merely a conserved cell type but a regeneration-optimized immune architecture evolved to balance pathogen defense with scar-free repairan insight with profound implications for regenerative medicine.

Cluster Context

This cluster comprises cells exclusively with immune_status "Immune" (100%). The majority originate from group "dpa3" (75%), with 12% from "dpa14". Sample distribution includes 25% from sum.3dpa1 (wound_healing_1), 20% from sum.3dpa2 (wound_healing_2), and 31% from sum.3dpa3 (wound_healing_3). Technically, 76% of cells are from batch1 and 19% from batch2. In clustering analyses, all cells (100%) belong to RNA_snn_res.0.5 cluster 4, 99% to cca_clusters 3, and in unintegrated_clusters, 77% from cluster 4 and 16% from cluster 7.
This cluster exhibits strong enrichment in innate immune system pathways (NES=6.50 in differential mode; NES=8.83 in singleSample mode), highlighting robust activation of immune responses. Neutrophil degranulation is prominently upregulated (NES=4.85 differential; consistent with immune themes in singleSample), indicating specialized granulocyte activity. Adaptive immune system processes are moderately enriched (NES=4.10 differential), complemented by toll-like receptor cascades (NES=4.10), suggesting integrated immune signaling. Transport of small molecules is enriched (NES=4.29 differential), aligning with cellular responses to stimuli (NES=7.48 singleSample). Downregulated pathways include collagen chain trimerization (NES=-4.74 differential) and elastic fiber formation (NES=-4.29), indicating reduced extracellular matrix assembly. Viral messenger RNA synthesis is downregulated (NES=-4.40 differential), possibly reflecting antiviral preparedness or lack of viral replication support. These patterns, supported by high NES values across Reactome analyses, underscore immune-centric functional coherence with diminished structural and developmental processes.

Disease Association

The identified cell populationAIF1+/CSF1R+/C1Q+ phagocytic tissue-resident macrophages with complement-mediated immune surveillance functiondoes not correspond to a classical disease state in the axolotl model, as these cells represent a physiological, activated state during limb regeneration. However, based on conserved mammalian biology, this phenotype is strongly associated with several human diseases characterized by lipid-laden or complement-activating macrophages. Key associations include Erdheim-Chester disease (DOID:4329), a non-Langerhans histiocytosis marked by proliferation of lipid-laden macrophages causing tissue sclerosis; pulmonary hemosiderosis (DOID:12118), where alveolar macrophages accumulate hemosiderin following microhemorrhage; and xanthogranulomatous cholecystitis (DOID:9766), defined by foamy macrophage nodules. The presence of C1Q and robust complement pathway activation suggests involvement in immune complex-mediated conditions such as immune-complex glomerulonephritis (DOID:4784) and hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (DOID:0050120), where macrophages exhibit excessive phagocytosis of hematopoietic cells. In the axolotl context, these macrophages are not pathogenic but are essential for debris clearance, immune regulation, and tissue remodeling during regeneration. Their activation without M1/M2 polarization reflects a homeostatic, non-inflammatory surveillance state unique to regenerative environments. Therapeutically, understanding how axolotl macrophages avoid fibrotic or chronic inflammatory outcomes could inform strategies to modulate human macrophage responses in fibrosis, autoimmunity, or failed regeneration.

Therapeutic Approach

The identified AIF1+/CSF1R+/C1Q+ tissue-resident macrophages in axolotl limb regeneration represent a unique activated, non-polarized surveillance state critical for debris clearance and immune regulation. While no FDA-approved drugs directly target axolotl macrophages, mammalian pharmacology provides strong translational insights. CSF1R inhibitors (e.g., pexidartinib, PLX3397) are clinically approved for tenosynovial giant cell tumor and selectively deplete CSF1R-dependent macrophages, suggesting potential to modulate this population in regenerative contexts where excessive or prolonged activation may impede redifferentiation. Conversely, C1 esterase inhibitors (e.g., berotralstat, human C1-INH) may dampen complement-mediated inflammation without eliminating phagocytic function, potentially preserving beneficial immune surveillance while reducing bystander tissue damagea strategy relevant to human conditions like hereditary angioedema and immune-complex glomerulonephritis. Safety considerations include risk of immunosuppression (increased infection) with CSF1R inhibition or fluid retention/hypertension with complement modulation. Emerging opportunities include targeted delivery of pro-regenerative cytokines (e.g., IL-10, TGF-) via nanoparticle carriers to these macrophages, or genetic reprogramming using CRISPRa/i to enhance their lipid-clearing (APOE/CD5L-driven) phenotype without inducing fibrosis. The axolotl model uniquely reveals how macrophages can be activated for regeneration without triggering chronic inflammation; understanding the endogenous regulators of their non-M1/M2 state could yield novel therapeutics for human fibrotic diseases, non-healing wounds, and failed regeneration.

Justification

Re-evaluation Based on Feedback

The feedback raises critical questions about: (1) whether KRT8 expression represents epithelial contamination or axolotl-specific mesenchymal adaptation, (2) whether canonical fibroblast markers from skin/hindlimb contexts are expressed at expected levels, and (3) whether this heterogeneous cluster should be split or annotated as a heterogeneous population. After comprehensive re-analysis, the fibroblast annotation remains the most appropriate, but with important refinements to acknowledge the cluster's heterogeneity and regenerative plasticity.

Investigation of KRT8 Expression (64.55%)

Evidence Against Epithelial Contamination:

  • KRT8 (64.55%) is elevated, but other epithelial markers are absent or very low: KRT19 (0%), EPCAM (5.12% vs 29.51%), CDH1 (0.58% vs 17.32%)
  • KRT18 (30.58% vs 20.6%) shows modest elevation, but the lack of KRT19 (which typically pairs with KRT8/18 in simple epithelia) argues against true epithelial identity
  • If this were epithelial contamination, we would expect coordinated expression of multiple epithelial markers, which is not observed

Evidence for Axolotl-Specific Regenerative Adaptation:

  • In the context of axolotl limb regeneration, cellular plasticity is a hallmark feature where cells can transiently express non-canonical markers
  • The co-expression of KRT8 with extremely high fibrillar collagens (COL1A1 74.5%, COL1A2 75.3%, COL3A1 68.73%) and VIM (92.15%) suggests these are mesenchymal cells with keratin expression, not epithelial cells
  • The pathway enrichment shows robust ECM assembly (NES > 4.8) and YAP1-ECM axis regulation (NES 5.2), which are characteristic of mechanosensitive fibroblasts, not epithelia
  • Interpretation: KRT8 expression likely represents a regeneration-associated phenotype where fibroblasts acquire intermediate filament diversity during active tissue remodeling, rather than epithelial contamination

Canonical Fibroblast Markers from Skin/Hindlimb Contexts

Markers Expressed at Expected or Elevated Levels:

  • LUM (Lumican): 18.6% vs 15.55% - slightly elevated, appropriate for dermal fibroblasts
  • COL6A1: 19.69% vs 14.48% - elevated, supporting fibroblast identity
  • COL6A2: 15.87% vs 14.34% - at expected levels
  • COL6A3: 20.38% vs 16.01% - elevated, consistent with active ECM production
  • FBLN1 (Fibulin-1): 16.09% vs 8.47% - nearly doubled, strongly supporting fibroblast identity in connective tissue remodeling

Markers Lower Than Expected:

  • DCN (Decorin): 6.72% vs 16.46% - substantially lower than other clusters
  • PDGFRA: 3.6% vs 8.62% - lower than expected
  • PDGFRB: 2.54% vs 7.64% - lower than expected
  • THY1 (CD90): 0.11% vs 0.33% - very low

Interpretation of Lower Markers:
The lower expression of DCN, PDGFRA, and PDGFRB suggests this is not a typical quiescent dermal fibroblast population, but rather a specialized subset of regenerative fibroblasts. Several possibilities:

  1. Differentiation state: These cells may represent more differentiated, matrix-producing fibroblasts that have downregulated growth factor receptors
  2. Fibroblast heterogeneity: Different fibroblast subtypes have distinct marker profiles; the extremely high COL1A1/COL1A2/COL3A1 expression suggests these are "matrix fibroblasts" rather than "reticular fibroblasts"
  3. Regenerative context: During active regeneration, fibroblast marker profiles may differ from homeostatic skin/limb fibroblasts

Critical Point: The presence of elevated LUM, COL6A1/2/3, and FBLN1 alongside the dominant fibrillar collagen signature provides sufficient evidence for fibroblast identity, despite lower DCN and PDGFR expression.

Heterogeneity Analysis: Should This Cluster Be Split?

Evidence for Three Distinct Subpopulations:

  1. Proliferating Fibroblasts:

    • PCNA (29.79% vs 22.98%), TOP2A (9.7% vs 7.79%), CDK1 (7.05% vs 4.39%), CCNB1 (5.09% vs 2.55%)
    • DNA repair/replication pathways upregulated (NES > 4.0)
    • Cell cycle control pathways enriched (NES > 4.0)

  2. KRT8-High Cells:

    • KRT8 (64.55% vs 30.24%), KRT18 (30.58% vs 20.6%)
    • SNAI1 (29.13% vs 11.81%) elevated, suggesting some EMT-related transcriptional activity
    • May represent a transitional or plastic state during regeneration

  3. Chondrogenic-Primed Cells:

    • COL2A1 (28.88% vs 15.99%), ACAN (8.43% vs 4.67%), COL9A1 (11.81% vs 6.87%), COL11A1 (42.14% vs 29.03%), COL11A2 (11.88% vs 7.83%)
    • TGF-beta/Smad signaling upregulated (NES > 3.8)
    • Cartilage development pathways enriched (NES > 4.0)

Arguments Against Splitting:

  • All subpopulations share the core fibroblast signature: COL1A1, COL1A2, COL3A1, VIM, FN1 are universally high across the cluster
  • Biological coherence: These states likely represent a continuum of fibroblast differentiation/activation during regeneration rather than distinct cell types
  • Temporal context: 73% from dpa23 and 18% from dpa14 suggests these are fibroblasts at specific regeneration stages where heterogeneity is expected
  • Functional unity: All cells are contributing to ECM assembly and tissue remodeling, which is the primary function during medium bud stages

Arguments For Acknowledging Heterogeneity:

  • The cluster context explicitly states "heterogeneity status is True"
  • The coexistence of proliferating, KRT8-high, and chondrogenic markers suggests functional diversity
  • Different subpopulations may have distinct roles in regeneration (proliferation vs. matrix production vs. lineage priming)

Decision: Rather than splitting, this cluster should be annotated as a heterogeneous population of regenerative fibroblasts with multiple functional states. This approach:

  • Maintains biological plausibility (fibroblasts are known to be heterogeneous)
  • Reflects the regenerative context where plasticity is expected
  • Acknowledges the shared core identity while recognizing functional diversity
  • Aligns with the temporal distribution showing active tissue remodeling

Comparison with C2S-Scale Prediction

The feedback mentions that C2S-Scale predicts "epithelial cell" based on marker genes. However, this prediction appears to be driven primarily by KRT8 expression and does not account for:

  • The overwhelming fibrillar collagen signature (COL1A1, COL1A2, COL3A1 all >68%)
  • The absence of other epithelial markers (KRT19, EPCAM, CDH1 all very low)
  • The robust ECM assembly pathway enrichment
  • The biological context of axolotl regeneration where marker expression may be non-canonical

The fibroblast annotation is more consistent with the totality of evidence than an epithelial classification.

Blastema Marker Expression

Interestingly, posterior HOX genes show elevation: HOXA13 (8.06% vs 1.27%), HOXA11 (4.21% vs 1.37%), HOXD13 (1.67% vs 0.99%), HOXD11 (3.31% vs 2.71%), HOXD10 (3.41% vs 2.25%). However, key blastema transcription factors remain low: PRRX1 (1.67% vs 3.61%), MSX1 (0.47% vs 0.8%), MEIS1 (1.2% vs 5.34%). This pattern suggests:

  • These fibroblasts retain positional identity (HOX code) appropriate for limb regeneration
  • They are not dedifferentiated blastema progenitors (low PRRX1, MSX1, MEIS1)
  • They represent differentiated fibroblasts contributing to regeneration while maintaining their positional information

EMT Marker Analysis

SNAI1 (29.13% vs 11.81%) is notably elevated, while SNAI2 (2.65% vs 8.66%) and ZEB2 (4.54% vs 9.38%) are lower. ZEB1 (7.66% vs 5.17%) shows modest elevation. This mixed EMT signature suggests:

  • Not active EMT (would expect coordinated elevation of multiple EMT transcription factors)
  • SNAI1 elevation may reflect its role in fibroblast activation and ECM remodeling rather than epithelial transition
  • The cells have already completed any EMT-like transition and are established mesenchymal cells

Proliferation Profile

The proliferation markers show an interesting pattern:

  • S-phase markers elevated: PCNA (29.79% vs 22.98%), TOP2A (9.7% vs 7.79%)
  • M-phase markers elevated: CDK1 (7.05% vs 4.39%), CCNB1 (5.09% vs 2.55%)
  • G1/S transition markers lower: CCND1 (9.92% vs 25.33%), CCNE1 (1.38% vs 2.44%)
  • Overall proliferation marker: MKI67 (17.14% vs 22.35%) is actually lower

This suggests a subset of cells are actively proliferating (S and M phase), but the overall proliferation rate may not be higher than other clusters. This supports the heterogeneity interpretation where some cells are proliferating while others are in G0/G1 focusing on matrix production.

Final Decision and Annotation Strategy

Core Identity: Fibroblast - this remains the most appropriate annotation based on:

  1. Extremely high fibrillar collagen expression (COL1A1, COL1A2, COL3A1)
  2. Robust ECM assembly pathway enrichment
  3. Presence of canonical fibroblast markers (LUM, COL6A1/2/3, FBLN1, FN1, VIM)
  4. Appropriate negative markers (immune, endothelial, muscle all low/absent)
  5. Biological context of connective tissue regeneration at medium bud stages

Heterogeneity Acknowledgment: The granular annotation and cell state fields should explicitly recognize the heterogeneous nature with multiple functional subpopulations.

KRT8 Expression: Interpreted as a regeneration-associated adaptation rather than epithelial contamination, included in the granular annotation to capture this unique feature.

Chondrogenic Potential: Maintained in the annotation as the elevated cartilage markers (COL2A1, ACAN, COL9A1, COL11A1/2) and TGF-beta signaling indicate a subset of cells are primed for chondrogenic differentiation.

Cell State: Updated to "heterogeneous: proliferating, chondrogenic-primed" to explicitly acknowledge the multiple functional states coexisting in this cluster.

This annotation strategy balances the feedback's concerns about heterogeneity while maintaining the well-supported fibroblast identity, acknowledges the unusual KRT8 expression as a regenerative adaptation, and recognizes that the lower DCN/PDGFR expression reflects a specialized regenerative fibroblast subset rather than contradicting the core identity.

Review Comments

Expert Assessment Integration

The five expert assessments converge on a unified core conclusion: this cluster represents a specialized population of regenerative fibroblasts, not epithelial cells or dedifferentiated progenitors. While experts diverge on mechanistic interpretationsparticularly regarding YAP-ECM axis activity and chondrogenic primingthey unanimously affirm the fibroblast identity based on the overwhelming, cluster-defining expression of fibrillar collagens (COL1A1: 74.5%, COL1A2: 75.3%, COL3A1: 68.73%) and mesenchymal markers (VIM: 92.15%, FN1: 55.79%). The complete absence of KRT19, EPCAM, and CDH1 definitively refutes epithelial contamination as an alternative interpretation. The downregulation of classical fibroblast markers (DCN: -59%, PDGFRA/B: -60%+, THY1: >96% reduction) is not viewed as contradictory but rather as evidence of phenotypic specialization toward a mature ECM-synthesizing state unique to axolotl regeneration.

Biological Context

This cluster emerges at dpa23/dpa14 timepoints during medium-bud limb regeneration, precisely when structural reorganization of the blastema occurs. The high expression of HOXA13 and HOXA11 confirms these cells retain precise posterior positional identitya critical feature distinguishing them from pluripotent-like progenitors that express PRRX1/MSX1. Unlike mammalian wound healing where fibroblasts rapidly activate into myofibroblasts via ACTA2 and YAP signaling, these axolotl fibroblasts exhibit a distinct phenotype: they are matrix factories with minimal contractile machinery (ACTA2 < 7%), suppressed integrin signaling (ITGB1 = 0%), and no detectable chemotactic ligands for immune recruitment (CCL2/CXCL8 = 0%). This suggests a decoupling of matrix production from mechanical feedback or inflammatory crosstalkan evolutionary adaptation enabling rapid scaffold deposition without triggering fibrotic responses.

Confidence & Heterogeneity Considerations

The High confidence level is justified by unanimous expert consensus on the core identity, reinforced by quantitative gene expression thresholds far exceeding background levels across multiple independent markers. The heterogeneity status is not merely technical but biologically profound: three functionally coherent subpopulations coexist within a single lineageproliferating cells marked by PCNA/TOP2A/CDK1 elevation; KRT8-high cells exhibiting cytoskeletal plasticity without epithelial commitment; and chondrogenic-primed subsets expressing COL2A1/ACAN/COL11A1 despite low SOX9/RUNX2 levels. This heterogeneity reflects a continuum of activation states rather than discrete lineages, consistent with the dynamic nature of regeneration where fibroblasts transition from proliferation to matrix synthesis to lineage priming within a single microenvironmental niche.

Alternative Interpretations

While some experts questioned whether this could represent 'mesenchymal stromal cells' or 'dermal papilla-like' populations, these alternatives fail because they lack defining markers (CD73, CD44) or are inconsistent with spatial context in regenerating limbs. The most compelling alternative interpretationthat these are 'passive remodelers' using non-canonical pathwaysis supported by the paradoxical absence of YAP/TAZ despite massive collagen output. This suggests axolotl fibroblasts may utilize alternative mechanosensors like Rho GTPases or integrin-independent transcriptional programs to drive ECM synthesisa phenomenon potentially unique to highly regenerative species.

Biological Significance

This cluster embodies the essence of axolotl regenerative success: fibroblasts as multifunctional architects capable of simultaneously producing structural scaffolds while retaining lineage plasticity. The co-expression of KRT8 with fibrillar collagens reveals an unprecedented adaptation where intermediate filament diversity enhances resilience during tissue remodeling under mechanical stress. The chondrogenic priming without terminal differentiation suggests these cells serve as a reservoir of positional memory poised to respond to future morphogenetic cuesnot committed precursors but flexible contributors to endochondral patterning. Critically, their isolation from inflammatory signaling implies regeneration proceeds through tightly regulated compartmentalization of functionsfibroblasts build structure while other cell types manage immunity or vascularization. This functional segregation may be key to avoiding scarring in mammals.

Cluster Context

The cluster comprises 100% non-immune samples, with 73% from the dpa23 group and 18% from the dpa14 group, reflecting later and earlier stages of the experimental time course. Sample composition includes 37% from sum.23dpa4, 20% from sum.S2, and 13% from sum.S3, corresponding to sample IDs of 37% medium_bud_1, 20% medium_bud_4, and 13% early_bud_1. Technical factors show 48% from batch1 and 44% from batch2, with the cluster aligning 100% to RNA_snn_res.0.5 cluster 5, 79% to cca_clusters 7 and 15% to 20, and distributions of 49% in unintegrated_clusters 6, 18% in 28, and 12% in 17.
In differential analysis, this cluster exhibits strong downregulation of innate and adaptive immune system pathways (NES < -6.0 in Reactome), including cytokine signaling, neutrophil degranulation, and responses to infectious and viral stimuli, alongside reduced activity in cellular stress responses and membrane trafficking processes (NES < -7.0). Signaling pathways such as Rho GTPase signaling, receptor tyrosine kinase signaling, and NF-kappaB regulation are also significantly downregulated (NES < -4.0 in GO and Reactome), indicating lower intracellular signal transduction and inflammatory responses relative to other clusters. In contrast, the cluster shows robust upregulation of developmental morphogenesis pathways, including regulation of cartilage development, endochondral bone morphogenesis, endothelial cell differentiation, and ureteric bud branching (NES > 4.0 in GO), supported by TGF-beta/Smad signaling and epithelial-mesenchymal transition in WikiPathways (NES > 3.8). DNA repair and replication processes are prominently enriched, with positive regulation of base-excision repair, mismatch repair mechanisms, leading/lagging strand synthesis, and nucleotide biosynthesis (NES > 4.0 in Reactome and GO), highlighting enhanced genomic maintenance. Extracellular matrix assembly pathways, such as collagen fibril crosslinking, trimerization, and anchoring fibril formation, are upregulated (NES > 4.8 in Reactome), with crosstalk to YAP1-ECM axis regulation (NES 5.2 in WikiPathways). Chemotaxis regulation for granulocytes, macrophages, and leukocytes is increased (NES > 3.9 in GO), alongside prostaglandin biosynthesis and HDL particle remodeling (NES > 4.2). Cell cycle control pathways, including mitotic sister chromatid separation, spindle checkpoint, and exit from mitosis, display moderate upregulation (NES > 4.0 in GO). These differential patterns are complemented by single-sample analysis showing general upregulation of developmental biology and nervous system development (NES > 4.4 in Reactome), providing high-confidence cluster-specific context for morphogenesis and genomic integrity over immune activation.

Disease Association

This cluster of regenerative fibroblasts in the axolotl limb regeneration model does not represent a disease state per se, but rather a highly specialized, physiologically adaptive cell population involved in tissue repair. The cells exhibit a unique molecular signature characterized by high expression of fibrillar collagens (COL1A1, COL1A2, COL3A1), ECM assembly pathways (NES > 4.8), and chondrogenic priming markers (COL2A1, ACAN, COL11A1/2), alongside transient KRT8 expressiona phenomenon likely representing mesenchymal plasticity during regeneration rather than epithelial contamination. While no direct human disease is modeled here, the biological processes observed have strong parallels with pathological fibrosis and connective tissue disorders. For instance, dysregulated ECM deposition and persistent fibroblast activation are hallmarks of fibrosis-related diseases such as oral submucous fibrosis (DOID:5773), where fibroblasts drive progressive submucosal scarring. Similarly, excessive collagen crosslinking and YAP1-ECM axis hyperactivation mirror mechanisms seen in systemic sclerosis and cardiac fibrosis. The chondrogenic-primed subpopulation suggests potential for ectopic cartilage formation, akin to heterotopic ossification syndromes or osteoarthritis-associated metaplasia. Importantly, the cluster's robust DNA repair and replication activity (NES > 4.0) contrasts sharply with disease contexts like immunodeficiency 26 (DOID:0111961), where fibroblast DNA repair defects underlie genomic instability; here, enhanced repair supports regeneration fidelity. The absence of immune pathway activation further distinguishes this from inflammatory fibrotic conditions such as IPEX syndrome or IMD57, which involve immune-driven fibroblast stimulation. Thus, while this cluster is not pathological, it provides an evolutionary blueprint for controlled ECM remodeling that could inform therapeutic strategies to suppress maladaptive fibrosis in humans by mimicking axolotl-like precision in fibroblast regulation.

Therapeutic Approach

The regenerative fibroblast cluster identified in axolotl limb regeneration exhibits a unique molecular signature characterized by high expression of fibrillar collagens (COL1A1, COL1A2, COL3A1), ECM assembly pathways, and chondrogenic priming markers (COL2A1, ACAN), alongside activation of the YAP1-ECM axis and TGF-beta/Smad signaling. While no FDA-approved drugs directly target this specific fibroblast phenotype in humans, several therapeutic strategies emerge from mechanistic parallels with fibrotic diseases. TGF-beta inhibitors such as fresolimumab (an anti-TGF-beta monoclonal antibody) and galunisertib (a small-molecule TGF-beta receptor I kinase inhibitor) are under clinical investigation for systemic sclerosis and liver fibrosis and could potentially suppress the chondrogenic-primed subpopulation by blocking Smad-dependent differentiation. Similarly, emerging YAP1 inhibitors like verteporfin which disrupts YAP-TEAD transcriptional activity may attenuate pathological ECM overproduction without impairing regeneration fidelity. Notably, allogeneic cultured dermal fibroblasts (e.g., Stratagraft) represent a cell-based therapeutic approach that leverages fibroblast ECM production for wound healing, suggesting that controlled activation of this phenotype could be harnessed therapeutically. Safety considerations include risks of ectopic calcification or fibrosis if inhibition is too broad; thus, precision targeting via biomarkers like KRT8 or COL11A1 expression may enable selective modulation of proliferating or chondrogenic subpopulations. Future opportunities lie in developing small molecules that mimic axolotl-like regulation: enhancing DNA repair while suppressing persistent ECM deposition, potentially through transient modulation of Hippo/YAP signaling or epigenetic regulators of collagen gene expression. This cluster provides an evolutionary blueprint for scarless regeneration, offering novel targets to convert human fibrotic responses into regenerative outcomes.

Justification

Evidence Analysis and Final Decision

Initial Hypothesis Evaluation

After comprehensive analysis of all five hypotheses and their supporting/conflicting evidence, Hypothesis 5 (Specialized Epithelial Cells) emerges as the most supported, though with important caveats that necessitate a broader "Epithelial Cell" annotation rather than a more specific glandular/secretory subtype.

Key Supporting Evidence for Epithelial Identity

Strong epithelial marker expression:

  • EPCAM at 41.46% (vs 27.08% in other clusters) - a definitive pan-epithelial marker
  • DSP (desmoplakin) at 51.26% (vs 33.94%) - critical desmosomal component
  • PKP1 (plakophilin-1) at 26.65% (vs 20.68%) - another desmosomal protein
  • PERP at 43.20% (vs 35.55%) - epithelial-specific apoptosis regulator
  • CDH1 (E-cadherin) at 18.81% - epithelial adhesion molecule
  • Claudins: CLDN1 at 13.57% and CLDN7 at 28.23% (vs 20.9%) - tight junction proteins
  • Simple keratins: KRT8 at 21.22% and KRT18 at 8.41% - characteristic of simple epithelia
  • S100A13 at 77.16% (vs 36.71%) - expressed in keratinocytes and epithelial cells

Appropriate negative markers:

  • PTPRC (CD45) at only 4.64% (vs 25.09%) - confirms non-immune status
  • CD68 at 1.24% (vs 14.48%) - excludes macrophage identity
  • Endothelial markers low: PECAM1 at 2.64%, CDH5 at 0.45%
  • Smooth muscle markers low: ACTA2 at 2.30%, TAGLN at 2.41%
  • Reduced proliferation: MKI67 at 15.68% (vs 22.44%), TOP2A at 4.03% (vs 8.17%) - consistent with differentiated state

Why Not More Specific Keratinocyte Annotation (Hypothesis 1)

While Hypothesis 1 (Keratinocytes) was initially attractive due to S100A13 expression, critical keratinocyte markers are completely absent:

  • Basal keratinocyte markers: KRT5 at 0%, KRT14 at 0%, KRT15 at 0%
  • TP63 at only 4.71% - essential for basal keratinocyte identity
  • ITGA6 at only 7.01% (vs 18.16% in other clusters)
  • Differentiated keratinocyte markers: KRT1, KRT10, IVL, LOR, FLG, SPRR1A, SPRR2A all at 0%

This complete absence of both basal and differentiated keratinocyte-specific keratins rules out a keratinocyte-specific annotation.

Why Not Fibroblast (Hypothesis 2)

Despite significant collagen expression (COL1A1 at 42.63%, COL1A2 at 46.14%, COL3A1 at 32.76%), the strong epithelial marker signature dominates:

  • EPCAM expression at 41.46% is incompatible with fibroblast identity
  • Desmosomal proteins (DSP, PKP1) at high levels are epithelial-specific
  • PDGFRA at only 3.88% (vs 8.6%) - key fibroblast marker is lower
  • POSTN at only 0.15% - very low for active fibroblasts

Why Not Perivascular or Schwann Cells (Hypotheses 3 & 4)

Hypothesis 3 (Perivascular): All key markers are lower than other clusters - PDGFRB at 1.43% (vs 7.71%), RGS5 at 0%, NOTCH3 at 0%, MCAM at 1.62% (vs 11.4%). The strong epithelial signature contradicts this identity.

Hypothesis 4 (Schwann Cells): Despite S100A13 expression, all Schwann-specific markers are lower than other clusters - MPZ at 1.77% (vs 5.87%), PMP22 at 2.26% (vs 11.39%), SOX10 at 1.39% (vs 6.23%), S100B at 0%. The epithelial markers are incompatible with glial identity.

Mixed Epithelial-Mesenchymal Characteristics

The unusual feature of this cluster is the co-expression of epithelial markers with mesenchymal collagens and moderate VIM (39.05%). This is biologically plausible in the context of axolotl limb regeneration, where:

  1. Epithelial cells may undergo partial epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) during regeneration
  2. Wound epithelium in regenerating limbs can express both epithelial and some mesenchymal markers
  3. The downregulation of basement membrane components (COL4A1, COL4A2, LAMA1, LAMB1, LAMC1 all lower than other clusters) suggests these cells may be in a transitional or specialized state

Why Specialized/Glandular Subtype Is Not Warranted

While Hypothesis 5 suggested glandular/secretory epithelium, key markers are absent:

  • KRT19 at 0% (common in glandular epithelium)
  • MUC1 at only 1.13%
  • CLDN4 at 0%
  • TACSTD2 at 0%

The presence of simple keratins (KRT8/KRT18) without glandular-specific markers suggests a simple epithelial rather than specialized glandular identity.

Biological Context Integration

The cluster composition (48% from limb group, 34% from 23 dpa, 17% from 3 dpa, with representation in both regenerating and non-regenerating samples) suggests these are constitutive epithelial cells present throughout regeneration. The pathway analysis showing downregulation of proliferation, immune responses, and developmental pathways indicates these are differentiated, non-proliferative epithelial cells maintaining tissue integrity rather than actively regenerating progenitors.

Conclusion

The annotation "Epithelial Cell" is the most accurate and conservative choice, supported by strong pan-epithelial markers (EPCAM, DSP, PKP1, claudins, simple keratins) while avoiding over-specification given the absence of lineage-specific markers (keratinocyte keratins, glandular markers). The granular annotation captures the mixed epithelial-mesenchymal characteristics relevant to the regeneration context. This represents a synthesis of the evidence rather than selection of a single hypothesis, recognizing that these cells show clear epithelial identity with regeneration-associated features.

Review Comments

Expert Assessment Integration

The five expert assessments converge on a singular, profound insight: this cluster represents a regeneration-adapted epithelial hybrid, not a contamination or artifact. While classical mammalian biology would reject co-expression of EPCAM/DSP with COL1A1/COL1A2 as biologically implausible, all experts agree this is a functional innovation unique to axolotl limb regeneration. The high expression of DSP (51.26%) and PKP1 (26.65%) confirms intact desmosomesruling out fibroblast identitywhile the elevated S100A13 (77.16%) is interpreted not as keratinocyte commitment but as a stress-responsive, regeneration-specific calcium-binding protein upregulated in wound epithelium. Crucially, the suppression of EMT transcription factors (SNAI1/2, ZEB1/2) and TGF- signaling components indicates this is not a transient transition state but a stable, transcriptionally programmed phenotype.

Biological Context

This cell type emerges within the dynamic microenvironment of regenerating axolotl limbs, where rapid re-epithelialization must occur alongside coordinated stromal remodeling. Unlike mammals, where epithelial-mesenchymal crosstalk is mediated by paracrine signals from separate cell populations, the axolotl has evolved direct cellular plasticity: epithelial cells themselves deposit provisional collagen matrices to scaffold blastema migration beneath the wound epidermis. The downregulation of basement membrane components (LAMA1, LAMB3, COL4A1/2) is not a defectit is an adaptive dissolution of structural barriers to enable bidirectional signaling between surface epithelium and underlying mesenchyme. This explains their presence across 3 dpa and 23 dpa samples: they are not transient intermediates but persistent architectural contributors throughout regeneration.

Confidence & Heterogeneity Considerations

The High confidence rating is fully justified: the epithelial signature is not merely dominantit is definitive. No expert questioned EPCAM or DSP expression levels; the controversy lies only in interpreting the mesenchymal co-expression. The heterogeneity status as False is equally robust: the uniformity of expression across batches (batch1-3), time points (3 dpa to 23 dpa), and non-regenerating controls (Contra1/3) confirms homogeneity. This is not a mixture of epithelial cells and fibroblasts; it is one cell type expressing two seemingly contradictory programs simultaneouslya hallmark of evolutionary adaptation in regenerative organisms.

Alternative Interpretations

One plausible alternativethat these are transdifferentiated fibroblastsis refuted by the near-absence of PDGFRA (<4%) and PDGFRB (<2%), which are essential for fibroblast maintenance in both mammals and amphibians. Another hypothesisthat they are dedifferentiated keratinocytesis invalidated by the complete absence of KRT5/KRT14/KRT15 and low TP63 (4.71%). The most compelling alternative interpretation is that these represent epidermal progenitors primed for matrix production, but even this fails because KRT8/KRT18 expression is below cluster means, suggesting terminal differentiation rather than progenitor status.

Biological Significance

This discovery redefines our understanding of epithelial plasticity in regeneration. These cells function as structural engineers: maintaining barrier integrity via desmosomes while actively synthesizing ECM components typically reserved for fibroblasts. Their suppressed proliferation markers indicate they are not proliferating progenitors but differentiated effectors dedicated to tissue architecture. This dual role may explain why axolotls regenerate without scarringtheir epithelium doesn't just cover the wound; it helps rebuild it from within. In contrast, mammalian wounds recruit separate fibroblast populations that often over-deposit collagen, leading to fibrosis. This cluster reveals an evolutionarily optimized solution: one cell type performs multiple functions through context-dependent gene regulation, offering profound insights for regenerative medicine strategies aimed at mimicking scar-free healing.

Cluster Context

This cluster consists entirely of cells with non-immune status (100%), derived from various experimental samples in a limb regeneration time course, including 48% from limb group, 34% from 23 dpa group, and 17% from 3 dpa group. Sample composition shows 16% from non-regenerating Contra1, 12% from non-regenerating Contra3, 13% from wound healing 3dpa1, 11% from medium bud 23dpa5 medium_bud_2, 15% from medium bud 23dpa5, and 15% from S4. The cells are distributed across sequencing batches with 48% in batch3, 29% in batch1, and 23% in batch2. All cells are assigned to RNA_snn_res.0.5 cluster 6, with origins in unintegrated clusters 9 (13%), 17 (19%), 27 (19%), and 33 (14%), and CCA clusters 2 (17%), 8 (28%), and 11 (51%).
This cluster exhibits strong downregulation of immune system pathways, including innate and adaptive immunity, cytokine signaling, and responses to infectious and viral stimuli, as evidenced by highly negative NES values in differential analysis across multiple libraries. Transcriptional regulation and RNA metabolism processes are significantly downregulated relative to other clusters, with NES scores below -7 in Reactome and GO terms. Cell cycle progression, proliferation, and developmental biology pathways show marked suppression, highlighted by negative enrichment in mitotic processes and axon guidance. Stress response mechanisms and signaling by receptor tyrosine kinases are also diminished, contributing to a profile of reduced cellular responsiveness. Within the cluster, absolute expression reveals upregulation of broad immune-related pathways, contrasting with their relative downregulation. Neuronal signaling and synaptic processes, such as neurotransmitter release cycles and GPCR signaling, are strongly downregulated in single-sample analysis, with NES values around -4. Vascular endothelial growth factor signaling is downregulated in both modes, indicating reduced angiogenic activity. Protein catabolic processes, including ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation, are suppressed in differential analysis, suggesting altered protein homeostasis.

Disease Association

The identified epithelial cell cluster, characterized by EPCAM, DSP, and KRT8/18 expression with mixed epithelial-mesenchymal features, is not directly associated with any known human disease in the context of axolotl limb regeneration. However, the molecular signature of epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) observed hereco-expression of epithelial adhesion molecules and mesenchymal collagensis a hallmark of pathological processes in human epithelial cancers. Specifically, this signature mirrors mechanisms seen in transitional cell carcinomas (e.g., urothelial carcinoma of the bladder and renal pelvis), where epithelial cells undergo partial EMT to acquire invasive properties. In these malignancies, loss of basement membrane integrity and upregulation of VIM and collagen are associated with tumor progression, analogous to the downregulation of COL4A1/LAMA1 observed in this cluster. Importantly, while the axolotl cells exhibit EMT-like features during physiological regeneration (not pathology), their transcriptional profile closely resembles early stages of malignant transformation in human transitional epithelia. This suggests that the regenerative EMT program in axolotls may co-opt conserved molecular pathways that, when dysregulated in mammals, lead to carcinoma. The absence of proliferative markers and immune activation indicates these are not neoplastic but rather adaptive epithelial cells supporting wound closure and tissue remodeling. Thus, while no disease is directly associated with this cell type in regeneration context, its molecular profile provides an evolutionary model for understanding how controlled EMT can be uncoupled from proliferation to avoid malignant transformationa key insight for cancer biology and regenerative medicine.

Therapeutic Approach

This epithelial cell cluster, characterized by EPCAM and desmoplakin expression with mixed epithelial-mesenchymal features during axolotl limb regeneration, does not have direct FDA-approved drug targets specific to its molecular signature. While EPCAM and desmoplakin are critical epithelial adhesion molecules, no clinically approved drugs directly target these proteins in humans. However, the observed partial epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT) phenotypemarked by co-expression of epithelial markers and mesenchymal collagensmirrors molecular signatures seen in human transitional cell carcinomas. This suggests that drugs targeting EMT pathways may be relevant: for example, inhibitors of TGF- signaling (e.g., galunisertib) or Src family kinases (e.g., dasatinib), which are under investigation in urothelial carcinoma to reverse EMT-driven invasion. In the context of regeneration, these pathways are likely tightly regulated to prevent malignant transformation, making them attractive targets for regenerative medicine strategies aimed at enhancing controlled tissue remodeling without fibrosis or neoplasia. Safety considerations include avoiding broad EMT inhibition that could impair wound healing, as EMT is essential for re-epithelialization. Emerging opportunities include biomarker-guided modulation of EMT regulators such as SNAIL, TWIST, or ZEB1 using small molecules or RNA therapeutics, potentially enabling precise control over regeneration dynamics. This cluster thus provides a unique evolutionary model for understanding how physiological EMT can be uncoupled from proliferation, offering insights for cancer prevention and regenerative therapies in mammals.

Epithelial Cell

TP63-positive, EPCAM-expressing, S100-rich epithelial cell with transglutaminase activity, basement membrane attachment, and elevated antioxidant response

Missing Expression

Canonical mammalian keratins (KRT5, KRT14, KRT15) are absent, though axolotl-specific keratin-like LOC genes are highly expressed. Simple epithelial keratins KRT8/KRT18 are reduced rather than elevated. Mitochondrial genome-encoded genes remain absent.

Unexpected Expression

Exceptionally high expression of axolotl-specific keratin-like genes (LOC138521595, LOC138582385, LOC138521582 at 84-98%), S100 family proteins (LOC138516689, LOC138580439, S100A13 at 97-98%), and transglutaminase-like (LOC138580587 at 84.94%). EPCAM shows 3.5-fold enrichment (85.41% vs 24.15%) which is definitive for epithelial identity. Extremely high antioxidant gene expression (PRDX1: 94.7%, GSTP1: 92.43%) indicates strong oxidative stress adaptation.

User Provided Marker Genes

LOC138472539LOC138472546LOC138473690LOC138516039LOC138580587LOC138472538LOC138472540LOC138472541LOC138472545LOC138481506

Justification

Critical Re-evaluation Based on Annotated LOC Genes

The feedback provides crucial information about the LOC genes that dominate the top marker list. Analysis of these annotations reveals a strong epithelial signature that was previously underappreciated:

Key LOC Gene Annotations Point to Epithelial Identity

  1. Transglutaminase Activity: LOC138580587 is annotated as "protein-glutamine gamma-glutamyltransferase E-like" (84.94% vs 13.65% - 6.2-fold enrichment). This is consistent with TGM1 expression (32.25% vs 12.54% - 2.6-fold enrichment), indicating active cross-linking of structural proteins typical of epithelial differentiation and cornification.

  2. S100 Protein Family: Multiple LOC genes are S100-related:

    • LOC138516689: "protein S100-P-like" (98.8% vs 34.34%)
    • LOC138580439: "protein S100-G-like" (97.86% vs 32.77%)
    • S100A13: confirmed S100 family member (97.22% vs 35.37%)

    S100 proteins are calcium-binding proteins highly enriched in epithelial cells, particularly in keratinocytes and other stratified epithelia.

  3. Keratin-like Proteins:

    • LOC138521595: "keratin, type I cytoskeletal 47 kDa-like" (84.22% vs 25.46%)
    • LOC138582385: "keratin, type II cytoskeletal 5-like" (98.55% vs 34.67%)
    • LOC138521582: "keratin, type I cytoskeletal 15-like" (97.31% vs 36.3%)

    These keratin-like genes show massive enrichment (3-4-fold), indicating intermediate filament organization characteristic of epithelial cells.

  4. Annexin A1-like: LOC138510294 (92.13% vs 22.99% - 4-fold enrichment). Annexins are membrane-associated proteins involved in epithelial barrier function. This is supported by ANXA2 expression (74.42% vs 59.64%).

  5. Thioredoxin-like: LOC138516039 (88.75% vs 19.67% - 4.5-fold enrichment), consistent with the strong antioxidant signature (PRDX1: 94.7%, GSTP1: 92.43%).

Integration with Previous Progenitor Markers

The previous annotation correctly identified progenitor markers, but these should be reinterpreted in an epithelial context:

  • TP63 (18.52% vs 5.02%): TP63 is THE master regulator of epithelial stem cells and basal keratinocytes, not a general progenitor marker. Its expression definitively indicates epithelial lineage.

  • COL17A1 (36.48% vs 11.14%): COL17A1 is a hemidesmosomal component that anchors basal epithelial cells to the basement membrane. It's a marker of basal keratinocytes and epithelial stem cells.

  • Laminin-332 complex (LAMB3: 32.59%, LAMC2: 15.83%): These are basement membrane components secreted by basal epithelial cells to maintain epithelial-stromal attachment.

  • EPCAM (85.41% vs 24.15%): Epithelial Cell Adhesion Molecule shows 3.5-fold enrichment - this is a canonical epithelial marker that was not examined in the previous annotation but provides definitive evidence.

  • CDH1/E-cadherin (48.8% vs 14.1%): 3.5-fold enrichment in the epithelial-specific cadherin, essential for epithelial cell-cell adhesion.

Why Not Keratinocyte Despite Keratin-like Genes?

The absence of canonical mammalian keratins (KRT5, KRT14, KRT15 all 0%) initially seems contradictory, but this is explained by:

  1. Axolotl-specific keratins: The LOC-annotated keratin-like genes (LOC138521595, LOC138582385, LOC138521582) represent axolotl-specific keratin orthologs that may not have direct 1:1 correspondence with mammalian KRT5/14/15.

  2. KRT8/KRT18 reduction: These simple epithelial keratins are REDUCED (KRT8: 8.0% vs 34.01%, KRT18: 2.87% vs 22.45%), suggesting this is NOT a simple/glandular epithelium but rather a stratified or specialized epithelium that uses different keratin pairs.

  3. Regeneration-specific state: During axolotl limb regeneration, epithelial cells may express a unique keratin repertoire not captured by mammalian gene nomenclature.

Epithelial Cell Type Specificity

The combination of markers suggests this is a basal epithelial cell or epithelial progenitor:

  • Basal location markers: TP63, COL17A1, LAMB3, LAMC2 all indicate basement membrane attachment
  • Proliferative potential: TP63, SOX9 indicate stem/progenitor capacity
  • Differentiation activity: TGM1, S100 proteins, keratin-like genes indicate active differentiation
  • Barrier function: EPCAM, CDH1, ANXA2, S100A10 support epithelial barrier maintenance

Stress Adaptation in Regenerating Epithelium

The exceptional antioxidant signature (PRDX1: 94.7%, GSTP1: 92.43%, thioredoxin-like LOC138516039: 88.75%) makes biological sense for wound epithelium during regeneration:

  1. Epithelial cells at wound sites face oxidative stress from inflammation
  2. Regenerating epithelium must maintain redox balance during rapid migration and proliferation
  3. The NRF2 pathway upregulation (NES 4.5-6.0) is a protective response

Biological Context Integration

The cluster composition strongly supports epithelial identity:

  • 43% from wound healing stages (3dpa): Wound epithelium is the first tissue to cover the amputation site in axolotl regeneration
  • 38% from non-regenerating controls: Resident epithelial cells in intact limb skin
  • 100% non-immune: Consistent with epithelial lineage
  • Downregulated ECM organization: Epithelial cells don't produce bulk ECM; they produce basement membrane components (which ARE enriched: LAMB3, LAMC2, COL17A1)

Why Previous Annotation Missed This

The previous annotation focused on "progenitor" identity because:

  1. TP63 was interpreted as a general progenitor marker rather than epithelial-specific
  2. LOC gene annotations were not available, masking the keratin-like, S100, and transglutaminase signatures
  3. EPCAM and CDH1 were not examined
  4. The absence of mammalian KRT5/14/15 was over-interpreted as absence of keratin expression

Rejection of "Stress-Adapted Progenitor" Annotation

While the stress adaptation and progenitor features are real, they are secondary characteristics of an epithelial cell, not the primary identity. The annotation should reflect the cell lineage (epithelial) rather than its functional state (stress-adapted progenitor).

Confidence Assessment

High Confidence: The convergence of multiple independent lines of evidence provides strong support:

  1. LOC gene annotations reveal keratin-like (3 genes), S100 (3 genes), transglutaminase (1 gene), and annexin (1 gene) - all epithelial markers
  2. EPCAM (85.41%, 3.5-fold enriched) is a definitive epithelial marker
  3. CDH1 (48.8%, 3.5-fold enriched) confirms epithelial cell-cell adhesion
  4. TP63 (18.52%, 3.7-fold enriched) is the master epithelial transcription factor
  5. COL17A1 + laminin-332 indicate basal epithelial/basement membrane attachment
  6. Biological context (wound healing, skin tissue) is consistent
  7. Complete absence of fibroblast, immune, neural, and muscle markers

The only uncertainty is the exact epithelial subtype (basal keratinocyte vs. specialized epithelium), which may be axolotl-specific and not have a direct mammalian equivalent.

Review Comments

Expert Assessment Integration

The five expert assessments converge on a unified biological narrative: this cluster represents a regeneration-adapted basal epithelial progenitor with species-specific molecular adaptations. The T cell immunologist definitively ruled out immune contamination through exhaustive analysis of 30+ canonical markers, noting that elevated CD8A, CD40LG, and LAG3 lack coordinated immune signatures and likely reflect non-canonical epithelial expression under stress. The developmental biologist and functional epithelial biologist independently confirmed the dominance of axolotl-specific keratin-like genes (LOC138582385: 98.55%, LOC138521582: 97.31%) and S100 proteins (S100A13: 97.22%) as functional substitutes for mammalian keratins and differentiation effectors a key evolutionary divergence. The regenerative tissue pathologist and systems epithelial architect reinforced that the co-expression of EPCAM (85.41%), CDH1 (48.8%), TP63 (18.52%), COL17A1 (36.48%), and laminin-332 subunits forms an irrefutable epithelial adhesion signature, while the suppression of ECM genes reflects compartmentalization, not contamination.

Biological Context

This cell state is not merely "epithelial" but is functionally sculpted by regeneration. Its presence across both non-regenerating controls (38%) and wound-healing stages (43%) indicates it is not a transient injury response but a constitutive lineage of axolotl skin with heightened regenerative competence. The downregulation of Wnt, TGF-beta, and VEGF pathways aligns with the need to suppress fibrotic signaling during re-epithelialization, allowing migration without premature differentiation or collagen deposition a mechanism absent in mammals where scarring dominates. The absence of tight junctions (CLDN3/4/7 = 0%) suggests this is a migratory, not sealing, epithelium optimized for rapid wound coverage over the amputation plane, consistent with the amphibian requirement for rapid barrier restoration in aquatic environments.

Confidence & Heterogeneity Considerations

The high confidence annotation is justified by the convergence of lineage-defining markers across independent expert analyses and the absence of any competing signature for alternative lineages (fibroblast, immune, neural). The heterogeneity rationale is sound: apparent contradictions such as the absence of KRT5/KRT14 or low ITGA6/ITGB4 levels are not indicators of mixed populations but rather evolutionary adaptations unique to urodeles. The extreme enrichment of LOC genes (>97% for multiple loci) in a single cluster demonstrates transcriptional homogeneity; no expert identified subpopulations based on expression gradients or bimodal distributions. The uniformity of antioxidant gene expression (PRDX1: 94.7%, GSTP1: 92.43%, thioredoxin-like: 88.75%) further confirms a single, coordinated stress-response program rather than heterogeneous activation states.

Alternative Interpretations

While mesenchymal-to-epithelial transition was considered, it is refuted by the absence of mesenchymal markers like VIM (>60% in fibroblasts vs 29.7% here), FN1, or TWIST/SNAIL transcripts in adjacent clusters all critical to MET initiation are undetectable here. The hypothesis of ectopic immune gene expression remains plausible only if CD40LG/LAG3 serve as damage sensors on stressed keratinocytes, as suggested by the immunologist, but even then they do not alter the core identity they modulate its microenvironmental interaction without changing lineage commitment.

Biological Significance

This cluster reveals a fundamental principle of axolotl regeneration: lineage fidelity preserved through molecular innovation. Rather than relying on conserved mammalian keratins or transglutaminase isoforms, axolotl basal epithelia have evolved paralogous gene families to maintain structural integrity under mechanical stress during rapid migration a solution enabling scarless healing unmatched in mammals. The NRF2-independent antioxidant response suggests an ancient redox regulation pathway activated constitutively in these cells, potentially linked to their lifelong regenerative capacity perhaps even priming them for future injury responses without requiring de novo induction of stress pathways upon amputation. This cell type may represent the evolutionary cornerstone of regenerative competence: an anchored yet plastic epithelial progenitor capable of dynamic adaptation without losing identity, offering profound insights into how mammals might be coaxed toward similar resilience.

Cluster Context

This cluster comprises 100% non-immune samples, with cells distributed across experimental conditions including non-regenerating (38% total: 18% from non-regenerating_2 and 20% from non-regenerating_3) and wound healing stages (43% total: 12% from wound_healing_1, 20% from wound_healing_2, and 11% from wound_healing_3). Sample origins show 12% from sum.3dpa1, 20% from sum.3dpa2, 11% from sum.3dpa3, 18% from sum.Contra2, and 20% from sum.Contra3. Technical factors include batch distribution of 53% from batch1 and 40% from batch3. Group assignments indicate 40% from limb, 43% from dpa3, and 15% from dpa23.
This cluster exhibits strong downregulation of extracellular structure organization and collagen formation pathways, with NES values below -5.0 in differential analysis, indicating reduced extracellular matrix remodeling and structural maintenance. Cytoskeleton organization and cell-matrix adhesion processes are also significantly downregulated (NES < -4.5), suggesting diminished cellular motility and adhesion capabilities relative to other clusters. Signaling pathways involving TGF-beta receptor superfamily, Wnt, and VEGF are prominently suppressed (NES -3.9 to -5.0), highlighting cluster-specific attenuation of developmental and angiogenic signaling. In contrast, cellular respiration and biological oxidation pathways show upregulation (NES > 4.0), supported by enrichment in mitochondrial OXPHOS and electron transport chain components. The NRF2 pathway is moderately upregulated (NES 4.5-6.0 across libraries), pointing to enhanced antioxidant and stress response mechanisms. Downregulation of cell cycle progression and positive regulation of T cell activation (NES < -4.5) further characterizes reduced proliferative and immune activation states. Integration of single-sample results reinforces suppression of synaptic and neuronal adhesion pathways, aligning with differential findings on reduced cell projection organization. These patterns indicate coherent downregulation of structural and signaling processes alongside upregulated metabolic resilience.

Disease Association

This cluster represents a stress-adapted epithelial cell population with a basal keratinocyte-like identity, characterized by TP63, EPCAM, COL17A1, and S100 protein expression, alongside a robust NRF2-mediated antioxidant response. While no direct disease association is established in axolotls, the molecular signature strongly parallels human epithelial pathologies involving barrier dysfunction and oxidative stress. The most relevant human disease association is congenital diarrhea 5 with tufting enteropathy (DOID:0060776), which is caused by mutations in EPCAM and results in defective epithelial adhesion, disrupted basement membrane integrity, and chronic epithelial stress mirroring the high expression of EPCAM, laminin-332, and COL17A1 observed here. Additionally, the pronounced antioxidant response (PRDX1, GSTP1, thioredoxin-like genes) and suppression of ECM organization align with chronic wound epithelium in diabetic ulcers or radiation dermatitis, where persistent oxidative stress impairs re-epithelialization. The downregulation of TGF-beta and Wnt signaling suggests an arrested differentiation state, potentially analogous to non-healing epidermal niches in chronic skin diseases. In the context of axolotl regeneration, this cell type likely represents a protective, resilient epithelial progenitor that survives mechanical and oxidative stress at the wound margin to facilitate regeneration. Therapeutically, this cluster highlights conserved pathways of epithelial resilience that could be leveraged to enhance mammalian wound healing by modulating NRF2 activity or stabilizing EPCAM-mediated adhesion complexes.

Therapeutic Approach

This stress-adapted epithelial cell cluster, characterized by high EPCAM, TP63, and NRF2 pathway activation, represents a resilient basal epithelial progenitor critical for wound re-epithelialization in axolotl limb regeneration. While no FDA-approved drugs directly target EPCAM or TP63 due to their structural and transcriptional roles, the upregulated NRF2 pathway presents a compelling therapeutic node. Omaveloxolone (CHEBI:229661), an NRF2 activator approved for Friedreichs ataxia, enhances antioxidant gene expression (PRDX1, GSTP1) and mitigates oxidative stress directly aligning with this cluster's molecular signature. In human chronic wounds (e.g., diabetic ulcers), where epithelial redox imbalance impedes healing, omaveloxolone could promote re-epithelialization by stabilizing the stressed epithelial barrier. The downregulation of TGF-beta and Wnt signaling suggests arrested differentiation; combining NRF2 activation with localized Wnt agonists (e.g., lithium chloride in preclinical models) may restore regenerative competence. Safety considerations include potential off-target effects on keratinocyte proliferation if NRF2 is overactivated, which may paradoxically impair terminal differentiation. Emerging opportunities include topical delivery of NRF2 inducers (e.g., sulforaphane analogs) or biologics targeting EPCAM-mediated adhesion complexes to enhance basement membrane integrity. This cluster highlights conserved mechanisms of epithelial resilience that could be harnessed to convert non-healing mammalian wounds into regenerative environments by mimicking the axolotls endogenous protective response.
